NAME
       dig - DNS lookup utility

SYNOPSIS
       dig [@server] [-b address] [-c class] [-f filename] [-k filename]
           [-m] [-p port#] [-q name] [-t type] [-x addr]
           [-y [hmac:]name:key] [-4] [-6] [name] [type] [class]
           [queryopt...]

       dig [-h]

       dig [global-queryopt...] [query...]

DESCRIPTION
       dig (domain information groper) is a flexible tool for
       interrogating DNS name servers. It performs DNS lookups and
       displays the answers that are returned from the name server(s)
       that were queried. Most DNS administrators use dig to
       troubleshoot DNS problems because of its flexibility, ease
       of use and clarity of output.

       Unless it is told to query a specific name server, dig will
       try each of the servers listed in /etc/resolv.conf. On LikeOS,
       the kernel's built-in DNS resolver is used.

       When no command line arguments or options are given, dig will
       perform a NS query for "." (the root).

SIMPLE USAGE
       A typical invocation of dig looks like:

              dig @server name type

       where:

       server is the name or IP address of the name server to query.
              When the supplied server argument is a hostname, dig
              resolves that name before querying the name server.

       name   is the name of the resource record that is to be looked
              up.

       type   is the type of query required — ANY, A, MX, SIG, etc.
              type can be any valid query type. If no type argument
              is supplied, dig will perform a lookup for an A record.

OPTIONS
       -b address
              Set the source IP address of the query.

       -c class
              Set the query class. The default class is IN; other
              classes are HS for Hesiod records or CH for Chaosnet
              records.

       -f filename
              Batch mode: dig reads a list of lookup requests to
              process from the given file. Each line in the file
              should be organized in the same way they would be
              presented as queries.

       -k filename
              Name of the file containing the TSIG key.

       -m     Enable memory usage debugging.

       -p port#
              Send the query to a non-standard port on the server
              (default is 53).

       -q name
              The domain name to query. This is useful to distinguish
              the name from other arguments.

       -t type
              The resource record type to query. It can be any valid
              query type which is supported in BIND 9. The default
              query type is "A", unless the -x option is supplied.

       -x addr
              Simplified reverse lookups, for mapping addresses to
              names. addr is an IPv4 address in dotted-decimal
              notation.

       -y [hmac:]keyname:secret
              Sign the queries using TSIG with the given
              authentication key. Not supported on LikeOS.

       -4     Use IPv4 only.

       -6     Use IPv6 only (not supported on LikeOS).

       -h     Print a brief summary of command-line arguments and
              options.

QUERY OPTIONS
       dig provides a number of query options which affect the way
       in which lookups are made and the results displayed. Some of
       these set or reset flag bits in the query header, some
       determine which sections of the answer get printed, and others
       determine the timeout and retry strategies.

       Each query option is identified by a keyword preceded by a
       plus sign (+). Some keywords set or reset an option. These
       may be preceded by the string "no" to negate the meaning of
       that keyword.

       +[no]tcp, +[no]vc
              Use [do not use] TCP when querying name servers.

       +[no]ignore
              Ignore truncation in UDP responses instead of retrying
              with TCP.

       +domain=somename
              Set the search list to contain the single domain
              somename.

       +[no]search
              Use [do not use] the search list defined by the
              searchlist or domain directive in resolv.conf.

       +[no]aaonly, +[no]aaflag
              A synonym for +[no]aaonly (obsolete).

       +[no]adflag
              Set [do not set] the AD (authentic data) bit in the
              query.

       +[no]cdflag
              Set [do not set] the CD (checking disabled) bit in
              the query.

       +[no]cl
              Display [do not display] the CLASS when printing the
              record.

       +[no]ttlid
              Display [do not display] the TTL when printing the
              record.

       +[no]recurse
              Toggle the setting of the RD (recursion desired) bit
              in the query.

       +[no]nssearch
              When this option is set, dig attempts to find the
              authoritative name servers for the zone containing the
              name being looked up and display the SOA record.

       +[no]trace
              Toggle tracing of the delegation path from the root
              name servers for the name being looked up.

       +[no]cmd
              Toggles the printing of the initial comment in the
              output.

       +[no]short
              Provide a terse answer. The default is to print the
              answer in a verbose form.

       +[no]identify
              Show [or do not show] the IP address and port number
              that supplied the answer when +short is enabled.

       +[no]comments
              Toggle the display of comment lines in the output.

       +[no]stats
              Toggle the printing of statistics.

       +[no]qr
              Print [do not print] the query as it is sent.

       +[no]question
              Print [do not print] the question section of a query
              when an answer is returned.

       +[no]answer
              Display [do not display] the answer section of a
              reply.

       +[no]authority
              Display [do not display] the authority section of a
              reply.

       +[no]additional
              Display [do not display] the additional section of a
              reply.

       +[no]all
              Set or clear all display flags.

       +time=T
              Sets the timeout for a query to T seconds. The
              default timeout is 5 seconds.

       +tries=T
              Sets the number of times to try UDP queries to
              server to T instead of the default, 3.

       +retry=T
              Sets the number of times to retry UDP queries to
              T. The default is 2.

       +ndots=D
              Set the number of dots (D) that have to appear in
              name for it to be considered absolute.

       +bufsize=B
              Set the UDP message buffer size advertised using
              EDNS0 to B bytes.

       +[no]edns[=#]
              Specify the EDNS version to query with.

       +[no]multiline
              Print records like the SOA records in a verbose
              multi-line format.

       +[no]onesoa
              Print only one (starting) SOA record when performing
              an AXFR.

       +[no]fail
              Do not try the next server if you receive a SERVFAIL.

       +[no]besteffort
              Attempt to display the contents of messages which are
              malformed.

       +[no]dnssec
              Requests DNSSEC records be sent by setting the DNSSEC
              OK bit (DO) in the OPT record in the additional
              section of the query.

       +[no]nsid
              Include an EDNS name server ID request when sending a
              query.

EXAMPLES
       dig example.com
              Look up the A record of example.com.

       dig example.com MX
              Look up the MX records.

       dig @8.8.8.8 example.com
              Query Google's DNS server.

       dig example.com +short
              Display only the answer.

       dig -x 8.8.8.8
              Reverse lookup.

       dig example.com +noall +answer
              Show only the answer section.

       dig -f queries.txt
              Batch mode from file.

